# migrated from tests/cases/parrot.chat (gen346, hermetic + isolated;
# expectations aligned to current behaviour).
[mock hermetic]
!set PARROT0_BASE=
!set PARROT0_SESSION=
!set PARROT0_WORLD_FACTS=0
!set PARROT0_LANG=en
!reset

[test parrot]
# gen15 retired the gen0 parrot-echo: unparseable input gets honest
# non-understanding, never an echo and never a wrong "No.".
# gen55 (C5a) makes that honesty NON-REPEATING: the chatsim users showed that
# repeating "I don't understand that yet." verbatim is the #1 naturalness killer
# (a broken record). The classic line is fine ONCE, but a consecutive repeat
# varies — reflecting a salient word from the user, or an honest redirect — so no
# two replies in a row are identical. It still never feigns understanding.
> tell me a story about dragons
< I don't have story material for that topic yet -- I can tell one about a lighthouse, an old house on a quiet street, a stormy night, or a traveler at dusk.
# would repeat -> vary (no content word in "blah blah" -> an honest redirect).
# (gen189: a bare number like "12345" is now claimed by mod_input as a
# non-linguistic input, so this no-content-word case uses a stopword-ish phrase
# that still falls through to the non-repeating not_understood path.)
> blah blah
< I don't understand that yet.
# would repeat -> vary with an honest redirect (no content word in the turn)
> the quick brown fox
< I didn't quite catch that. What would you like to know?
# previous reply was not the classic wall, so the classic wall is fine again
> bonjour comment vas-tu
< I don't understand that yet.
# would repeat -> reflect a salient word so it feels heard (held-out: any word)
> asdf qwerty zxcv
< Hmm, I don't know about qwerty yet. Want me to learn about it?
